    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "can u go a bit deeper into the anaerobic glycolysis part? specifically how the acid buildup actually triggers that stinging sensation in the nerves. like what is the chemical trigger?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "During anaerobic glycolysis, the production of lactic acid accelerates as the muscles rely on anaerobic metabolism to generate energy quickly. High levels of lactic acid can stimulate nociceptors, sensory neurons responsible for detecting and transmitting pain signals, in the affected muscles. The chemical trigger behind this sensation is the accumulation of lactic acid itself, as well as the byproducts of glycolysis, such as pyruvic acid. Specifically, a molecule called bombesin is released and binds to a receptor, anorectal GPR119, that activates nociceptive signaling pathways, leading to the stinging sensation you experience during intense exercise.",
      "source": "target",
